(43, 13, 20, 42, 10, 16, 16, 'he that receiveth me receiveth him that sent me', 'Connection of Reception and Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between the sender and the sent. They highlight that receiving or rejecting the messenger directly correlates to receiving or rejecting the one who sent them.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 20, 42, 9, 48, 48, 'receiveth me', 'Connection of Reception and Greatness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of receiving others as a reflection of receiving Jesus and God. The phrase ''receiveth me'' appears in both, linking the act of receiving with spiritual significance.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 20, 40, 25, 40, 40, 'receiveth me', 'Connection of Reception and Action', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of receiving others as a reflection of receiving Christ. John 13:20 highlights that receiving those sent by Jesus equates to receiving Him, while Matthew 25:40 states that acts of kindness towards others are seen as acts towards Jesus Himself.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 20, 41, 9, 37, 37, NULL, 'Connection of Reception and Sending', 'Both passages emphasize the act of receiving as a means of receiving Jesus and the one who sent him. They highlight the relationship between the sender, the sent, and those who accept them.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 20, 40, 10, 40, 42, NULL, 'Connection of Reception and Reward', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of receiving those sent by Jesus. They highlight that receiving a messenger equates to receiving Jesus and, by extension, God. This connection underscores the significance of hospitality and acknowledgment in the faith community.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 20, 48, 4, 14, 14, 'receiveth whomsoever I send', 'Reception of Messengers', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of receiving messengers sent by God. In John, receiving those sent is equated with receiving Christ, while in Galatians, Paul is received as an angel of God, akin to Christ.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 20, 43, 12, 44, 48, NULL, 'Connection of Belief and Reception', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between receiving Jesus and believing in God. They highlight that to accept Jesus is to accept the one who sent him, reinforcing the unity of their mission.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 21, 40, 26, 21, 21, 'one of you shall betray me', 'Betrayal Foretold by Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' declaration that one of his disciples will betray him. The phrase ''one of you shall betray me'' appears in both accounts, highlighting the shared theme of impending betrayal.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 21, 43, 13, 18, 18, 'one of you shall betray me', 'Betrayal of Jesus Foretold', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal present in both passages. In John 13:21, Jesus reveals that one of his disciples will betray him, while John 13:18 references the fulfillment of scripture regarding betrayal by one who shares a meal with him.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 21, 41, 14, 18, 18, 'one of you shall betray me', 'Betrayal Foretold by Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of betrayal among Jesus'' disciples. They specifically mention that one of those eating with Him will betray Him, highlighting the gravity of the situation.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 21, 42, 22, 21, 22, 'one of you shall betray me', 'Betrayal Foretold by Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of betrayal, with Jesus explicitly stating that one of his disciples will betray him. The mention of betrayal in both contexts highlights the gravity of the situation and the inevitability of the events to come.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 21, 43, 12, 27, 27, 'troubled in spirit', 'Connection of Troubled Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of a troubled spirit. In John 12:27, Jesus expresses his inner turmoil, while in John 13:21, he is troubled in spirit due to impending betrayal.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 21, 40, 26, 38, 38, 'troubled in spirit', 'Emotional Turmoil of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the emotional distress of Jesus in both passages. In John 13:21, Jesus is ''troubled in spirit,'' while in Matthew 26:38, he expresses being ''exceeding sorrowful.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 21, 44, 1, 16, 17, 'one of you shall betray me', 'Connection of Betrayal by Judas', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal, as both passages reference Judas''s role in betraying Jesus. John 13:21 introduces the betrayal, while Acts 1:16-17 reflects on its fulfillment.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 22, 42, 22, 23, 23, 'doubting of whom he spake', 'Disciples'' Doubt and Inquiry', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' uncertainty about who would betray Jesus. The phrases ''doubting of whom he spake'' and ''enquire among themselves'' reflect their confusion and concern regarding the identity of the betrayer.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 22, 40, 26, 22, 22, 'doubting of whom he spake', 'Disciples'' Doubt and Sorrow', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' uncertainty about who would betray Jesus. In John, they are ''doubting,'' while in Matthew, they express sorrow and question, ''is it I?''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 22, 41, 14, 19, 19, 'doubting of whom he spake', 'Disciples'' Doubt and Sorrow', 'This connection highlights the disciples'' uncertainty and concern about betrayal. Both passages depict the disciples questioning their own fidelity, reflecting their inner turmoil.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 22, 1, 42, 1, 1, NULL, 'Disciples'' Doubt and Brothers'' Confusion', 'This connection highlights the theme of uncertainty among individuals in critical moments. Both passages emphasize the act of looking at one another in confusion, reflecting a shared experience of doubt and indecision.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 23, 43, 19, 26, 26, 'whom Jesus loved', 'Connection of Beloved Disciple', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship of love between Jesus and the disciple. The phrase ''whom Jesus loved'' links the beloved disciple in both contexts, highlighting his significance in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 23, 43, 20, 2, 2, 'whom Jesus loved', 'Connection of the Beloved Disciple', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of ''the disciple, whom Jesus loved.'' This connection highlights the significance of this disciple in key moments of the narrative, linking his presence at the Last Supper and the discovery of the empty tomb.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 23, 43, 21, 7, 7, 'whom Jesus loved', 'Connection of the Beloved Disciple', 'Both passages emphasize ''the disciple whom Jesus loved,'' linking the beloved disciple''s recognition of Jesus in John 21:7 to his intimate relationship with Jesus in John 13:23. This connection highlights the significance of the beloved disciple''s role in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 23, 66, 1, 16, 18, 'whom Jesus loved', 'Connection of Beloved Disciple and Christ', 'This connection highlights the intimate relationship between Jesus and his beloved disciple, which parallels the powerful revelation of Christ''s divine authority in Revelation. Both passages emphasize the closeness of Jesus to his followers and his eternal nature.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 23, 10, 12, 3, 3, NULL, 'Connection of Love and Intimacy', 'Both passages emphasize a deep bond and affection. In John, the disciple is described as being close to Jesus, while in 2 Samuel, the ewe lamb is cherished and nurtured, symbolizing love and intimacy.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 13, 23, 43, 13, 25, 25, 'leaning on Jesus’ bosom', 'Discipleship and Intimacy with Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the closeness of the disciple to Jesus, as one is described as ''leaning on Jesus’ bosom'' and the other as ''lying on Jesus’ breast.'' This connection highlights the intimate relationship and trust between Jesus and his beloved disciple.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
